  "meta": {
    "title": "Cholera in the Estuary: Vibrio and the Chitin Shell Bloom",
    "date": "2026-07-22",
    "lesson": "Vibrio cholerae persists in brackish estuaries by attaching to chitinous zooplankton exoskeletons (copepods, crab larvae). Chitin is a carbohydrate polymer, and V. cholerae expresses chitinases to degrade it for both nutrition and biofilm attachment, which also aids environmental survival between human outbreaks. Warm post-monsoon water temperatures and zooplankton blooms drive Vibrio population explosions, correlating with seasonal cholera outbreaks. This scenario models a copepod-rich estuary where a chitin-degrading Vibrio-like founder must exploit carbohydrate-dominant particles (molted shells and chitin flakes), competing with protein specialists, while grazers (copepods) and phage predation shape the population.",
    "citation": "Colwell, R.R. (1996) Science 274:2025; Huq et al. Appl Environ Microbiol 2005",
    "difficulty": "normal",
    "realWorldBasis": "Vibrio cholerae chitin-zooplankton association, Bay of Bengal estuaries"
  },
